WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.080
So today I am excited to talk about the 3rd edition of testthat.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:15.840
So I'm going to start by talking a little bit about what do I mean by that.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:18.799
You certainly want to know what a version of a package is, but what do I mean by this

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:21.040
being the 3rd edition of testthat.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:28.440
Then I'm going to talk through three big new features in this version, in this edition,

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:35.119
see how testthat now displays differences much more clearly using the waldo package.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:39.439
We'll talk about a new type of testing, a new type of testing to testthat called snapshot

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:40.520
tests.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:45.160
Very briefly talk about testing in parallel, multi-process testing, and then finally I'm

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.040
going to give you a real quick goody bag of a bunch of little small stuff that will hopefully

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:54.220
make your life a little bit easier when using testthat.

00:00:54.220 --> 00:01:00.139
So the big news with this release of testthat, this upcoming release, testthat 3.0, is we're

00:01:00.139 --> 00:01:03.900
going to introduce the idea of this 3rd edition.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:08.059
And I should say anything you're going to hear about today is also explained in more

00:01:08.059 --> 00:01:12.500
detail in vignettes on the testthat website, so if you want to learn more about anything

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:18.860
I say today, feel free to take a look at those vignettes, and if they don't explain, they

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:23.419
don't help you understand what's going on, please file an issue so we can learn better.

00:01:23.419 --> 00:01:28.980
So the basic idea of the addition is that we want to make breaking changes to testthat.

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:35.059
Testthat's like 10 years old or something, and there's a bunch of things in the package

00:01:35.059 --> 00:01:36.940
that we now regret.

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:40.580
But testthat's kind of a victim of its own popularity.

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:46.300
There's something like 4,000 or 5,000 packages on CRAN that use testthat, and many of them

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:47.300
are not actively developed.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:52.980
So there's no way we can change testthat without breaking a bunch of packages, and many of

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:58.059
these packages, since they wouldn't be maintained, they'd just end up off CRAN because people

00:01:58.059 --> 00:02:02.620
wouldn't have the energy to fix them.

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:08.100
So the idea of an addition is that this is something you have to deliberately opt into.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:12.380
So if you want to use many of the new features or all of the new features of testthat I talk

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:18.259
about today, you have to deliberately choose to use a 3rd edition of testthat.

00:02:18.259 --> 00:02:22.580
And to sort of do that, you basically have to add a line in your description file, config

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:24.860
slash testthat slash addition.

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:28.419
So if you don't do this, you'll continue to use the second edition, that's the existing

00:02:28.419 --> 00:02:29.419
behavior of testthat.

00:02:29.419 --> 00:02:35.220
If you do this, you'll get, if you do change this, you'll get a bunch of new features and

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.880
a bunch of things, which I'll explain shortly, which have gone away.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:46.699
So the kind of idea is that it should take hopefully, you know, less than 30 minutes

00:02:46.699 --> 00:02:48.940
to convert a package to use the 3rd edition.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:53.580
You know, it's a little bit of work, hopefully not too much work, but it just generally gets

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:56.500
you up to date with all of our best current best practices.

00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:02.059
And I should say, if this kind of idea of this addition idea is successful, it's something

00:03:02.059 --> 00:03:07.100
we're likely to try out in other packages, a way of allowing existing code to continue

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:14.339
working while giving you the choice to opt into a new set of behaviors.

00:03:14.339 --> 00:03:17.419
So additions will always be coupled with a major version.

00:03:17.419 --> 00:03:25.380
So that means testthat2 and everything else before this counts as the 2nd edition, testthat3.0

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:29.979
can use the 2nd edition, that's the default behavior, or you can opt into using the 3rd

00:03:29.979 --> 00:03:30.979
edition.

00:03:30.979 --> 00:03:34.660
And if one day, you know, many, probably multiple years down the line, we decide to introduce

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:40.500
a 4th edition, then that would be tied to testthat4.0.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:42.940
So what's going away in the 3rd edition?

00:03:42.940 --> 00:03:46.300
These are the things that are most likely to lead you to change your tests.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:51.100
So while the context function is going away, we've kind of been moving away from this for

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:55.979
quite some time in favor of just using the name of the test file.

00:03:55.979 --> 00:04:00.179
There's no need to kind of duplicate the information in the test file and another function, which

00:04:00.179 --> 00:04:04.139
you have to remember to update if you ever move your test files.

00:04:04.139 --> 00:04:09.820
We've also been lately in DevTools and use this building kind of a stronger coupling

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:13.419
between files in the R directory and files in the test directory.

00:04:13.419 --> 00:04:18.420
So that is a kind of a one-to-one correspondence, which gives you a bunch of handy keyboard

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:21.660
shortcuts and development tools.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:24.500
The very old expect that function is going away.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:31.820
This was the kind of first API, the first excessively clever API that testthat used

00:04:31.820 --> 00:04:34.179
with every test kind of had the flavor.

00:04:34.179 --> 00:04:39.540
You could read it like a sentence like testthat blah is true.

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:45.380
And I pretty quickly decided that that was excessively clever, not very good.

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:49.220
And so we're finally deprecating that for good.

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:57.220
Expect is we're deprecating in favor of expect S3 class, expect S4 class and expect type

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:01.700
of just to be more precise about what exactly you're trying to express.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:02.700
Expect equivalent.

00:05:02.700 --> 00:05:05.500
I'll talk about a little bit later, but we're basically that's just going to be an argument

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:08.540
to expect equal or expect identical.

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:14.220
Some of the mocking functions going away in favor of more featureful packages.

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:20.500
And then finally, we are moving away from set up and tear down in favor of test fixtures,

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:24.459
which I'm not going to talk about today, but there's a whole vignette about them if you

00:05:24.459 --> 00:05:27.220
want to learn more.

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:29.779
And hopefully that's kind of all I need to say.

00:05:29.779 --> 00:05:32.420
Just these are the functions that are going away.

00:05:32.420 --> 00:05:36.019
Like if you really, really believe any of these functions are important, like now's

00:05:36.019 --> 00:05:38.980
the time to speak up and say you want to keep these.

00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:45.059
Otherwise, when you switch to the third edition, rerunning your tests, you'll get deprecation

00:05:45.059 --> 00:05:50.500
messages telling you what to replace these functions with.

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:53.220
So that's kind of the stuff that's going away.

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:56.540
Now I want to focus on the cool new features.

00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:01.339
I think the feature you are most likely to encounter and the most likely to give you

00:06:01.339 --> 00:06:06.859
pleasure in your life is that comparisons with expect equal and expect identical or

00:06:06.859 --> 00:06:15.420
test failures with expect equal and expect identical are now much easier to understand.

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:19.459
So previously expect equal uses the base all.equal function.

00:06:19.459 --> 00:06:24.779
This was never really what all.equal was intended for, but it kind of did an okay job.

00:06:24.779 --> 00:06:28.779
But there's a few cases where it just doesn't give very useful output.

00:06:28.779 --> 00:06:36.059
And so here I'm comparing empty cars without the first column to empty cars, the full data

00:06:36.059 --> 00:06:37.059
set.

00:06:37.059 --> 00:06:40.420
And you'll notice I get a lot of output.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:44.899
What tells me that there's 10 string mismatches in the names, that doesn't really help me.

00:06:44.899 --> 00:06:49.140
It tells me there's a length mismatch and then it gives me a bunch of mean relative

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:50.140
differences.

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:55.540
So this certainly tells me that there's a difference, but it doesn't kind of concisely

00:06:55.899 --> 00:06:59.540
point me to the fact there's a column missing in this data frame.

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:02.700
So now we use Waldo.

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:05.980
So to use this, I'm just going to use this function called local edition.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:10.500
This is not something you generally need to use in your tests because you'll convert a

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.339
whole package to use a third edition.

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:18.380
But we provide this local edition function for writing stuff like this, for writing vignettes

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:21.579
so you can explain about this new edition.

00:07:21.579 --> 00:07:25.579
This just temporarily sets the edition to the third edition.

00:07:25.579 --> 00:07:31.459
So now we use the third edition and now this is the new Waldo output.

00:07:31.459 --> 00:07:36.820
So the kind of the first principle is that Waldo is going to give you the most important

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:38.500
differences first.

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:43.299
And in this case, I think the most important difference is that the lengths are different.

00:07:43.299 --> 00:07:50.380
And then it tells us what the names are, how the names have changed, lining up the old

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:57.059
names, lining up the actual names with the expected names.

00:07:57.059 --> 00:08:02.019
And then it uses color to highlight the fact that in the expected, there's another column

00:08:02.019 --> 00:08:03.540
called MPG.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:07.420
And then finally down here, we get an exact description that, well, the names are different,

00:08:07.420 --> 00:08:09.420
but the values are also different.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:13.339
The actual, it's absent.

00:08:13.339 --> 00:08:18.760
And as I read this, that is clearly not the case because it's absent from the expected.

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:21.440
So I think I've messed up the labels here.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:22.440
So I'll have to fix these.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:29.000
This should say expected MPG is absent, and this should say actual MPG is a double vector.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.719
So that just allows you, once I fix those labels, to precisely see what the differences

00:08:34.719 --> 00:08:37.000
are.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.679
So here I've switched to use the third edition.

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:42.359
Waldo then shows the most important differences first.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:48.400
It uses color to help highlight differences, and it always uses the names of things we

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:52.559
have possible, just because that makes it easier to understand exactly where the differences

00:08:52.559 --> 00:08:54.619
lie.

00:08:54.619 --> 00:08:59.200
So another little example here, I have a factor.

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:03.440
This is an ordered factor with one extra level.

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:08.320
When you look at the expect equal output from the second edition, you'll see like it kind

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:12.520
of tells you that they're different, but it's hard because it doesn't include the values

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:15.599
to know exactly what's changed.

00:09:15.599 --> 00:09:18.679
When we switch to the third edition, now we can see, well, there's a new element of

00:09:18.679 --> 00:09:19.679
the class vector.

00:09:19.679 --> 00:09:24.880
It's ordered, and there's a new element of the levels, which is D, and hopefully this

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:28.880
will make it much, much easier to see exactly what's gone wrong.

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.599
And certainly in my own, this is like, this is the number one reason I've been converting

00:09:32.599 --> 00:09:36.440
packages to use the third edition to test that, just because it makes things so much

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:42.039
easier to see when something's gone wrong.

00:09:42.039 --> 00:09:46.760
So if you want to learn more about Waldo, you can go to the Waldo website, which shows

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:51.479
a bunch of kind of examples, shows some of the principles.

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:56.039
A lot of the differences of the values are powered by this really nice package called

00:09:56.039 --> 00:10:04.280
diffopt by Brody Graslam, which uses the same algorithm as the diff utility on Linux, which

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:11.640
just makes it really easy to kind of narrow in exactly what has changed between two vectors.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:17.119
This change also makes it now possibly precise about what's the difference between expect

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:22.760
equal, expect identical, and expect equivalent, which are always a little vague in the past.

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:28.640
Now all of these functions are equivalent to expect identical, but with some extra arguments

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:29.640
set.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:34.880
So if you use expect equal, that's equivalent to expect identical, except that it ignores

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:38.119
small floating point differences.

00:10:38.119 --> 00:10:42.479
Or if you use expect equivalent, which is now deprecated, it's just the same as using

00:10:42.479 --> 00:10:46.919
expect equal or expect equivalent with ignore attribute equals true.

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:50.919
That's the only thing that expect equivalent does is it just ignores attributes.

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:53.919
Now we're going to make that precise in a function argument.

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:59.799
And then any other arguments in expect identical or expect equal are passed on to Waldo compare,

00:10:59.799 --> 00:11:06.559
which gives you the ability to kind of fine tune your comparisons as needed.

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:07.880
Now this is such a great idea.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:11.640
You might wonder, well, why can't it work for the second edition as well?

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:19.679
Well, unfortunately, when I implemented expect equal, it turns out that I made a rather silly

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:23.679
mistake when implementing the tolerance comparison.

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:29.119
So depending on exactly which code path it goes down, it computes the tolerance in slightly

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:30.119
different ways.

00:11:30.119 --> 00:11:35.479
One way it always uses the absolute tolerance, and one way it uses absolute or relative tolerance.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:38.559
So there's basically no way I did a few experiments.

00:11:38.559 --> 00:11:42.760
There's no way, regardless of which one I pick, it causes like hundreds of CRAN packages

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:43.760
to break.

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:49.080
So that's the main reason that this has to be in the third edition.

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:54.400
But there's a few other small things, particularly if you're testing code in a modeling package.

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:59.640
All.equal, which used to power expect equal, ignores environments of formulas and models.

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:04.239
Sorry, formulas and functions.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:11.280
Waldo does not, but it provides a couple of arguments to allow you to override that if

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:12.280
you need to.

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:16.359
And there's just a few other small things around like POSIX CT.

00:12:16.359 --> 00:12:19.520
So I think the behavior of Waldo is generally better.

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:23.280
It's a little bit stricter, and when it fails, it'll give you clearer results.

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.719
But we can't just turn it on for everyone because it would break a bunch of tests.

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:29.479
So you're going to have to deliberately opt into it.

00:12:29.479 --> 00:12:31.479
Okay, so that's Waldo.

00:12:31.479 --> 00:12:37.840
I think that's like kind of the number one feature, like, again, I have found it like

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:44.679
so useful when debugging tests myself to have that much, much, much clearer display.

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:48.159
The next big feature I want to talk about is snapshot testing.

00:12:48.159 --> 00:12:51.719
Again, this comes with a vignette, so if you want to learn more about it, you can read

00:12:51.719 --> 00:12:52.719
the vignette.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:57.880
If the vignette doesn't make sense, please file an issue so we can make it better.

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:03.159
But the basic idea is this is a new type of testing.

00:13:03.159 --> 00:13:10.719
So normally in unit tests, you describe the expected output using code.

00:13:10.719 --> 00:13:14.760
And in the vast majority of cases, this is a really, really good idea because it allows

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:17.159
you to kind of describe what you expect.

00:13:17.159 --> 00:13:23.679
And in some sense, the tests help document, because the tests are code and code is a means

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:24.760
of communication.

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:29.200
They kind of help describe the expected behavior of the functions as well.

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:33.719
But sometimes describing the expected output is just like really annoying, like if it contains

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:38.559
a bunch of special characters, like quotes or backslashes, you have to spend a bunch

00:13:38.559 --> 00:13:41.119
of time like carefully escaping them.

00:13:41.119 --> 00:13:45.200
And then when something goes wrong, it's hard to see exactly, like you've got to unescape

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:47.640
them in your head, and it's just a pain.

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:53.159
Or maybe it's very large, like maybe you want to check an entire HTML page or multiple paragraphs

00:13:53.159 --> 00:13:56.239
of text, as you expect.

00:13:56.239 --> 00:14:00.200
Or maybe it's not even something that you can easily describe with text.

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:02.840
It's an image.

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:03.840
Or something else.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:10.960
So the idea of a snapshot or golden test, which idea used in other programming languages

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:22.520
and other testing packages, and test that inspiration draws primarily from Jest, which

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:28.299
is a JavaScript testing package that Joe Chang shared his experiences with me a bunch

00:14:28.299 --> 00:14:32.440
and persuaded me that this was something really useful.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:37.599
But so the snapshot test, the key idea is that instead of recording the results inline

00:14:37.599 --> 00:14:41.080
in the test itself, they're stored in a separate file.

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:47.479
And test that provides a bunch of tools for looking after that, for managing that file.

00:14:47.479 --> 00:14:51.359
So it will create it automatically the first time you run it, and then it gives you tools

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:55.520
to update it when you decide there really has to be a change.

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:59.919
And if you've used verify output or expect known output, which we've never really advertised

00:14:59.919 --> 00:15:04.400
because we've never really been particularly happy with them, the snapshot tests basically

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:07.679
supersede those functions.

00:15:07.679 --> 00:15:11.080
So what does a snapshot test look like?

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:15.840
So here I'm just going to give you a quick simulation in the presentation, and I'll show

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.359
you what this looks like in a real package.

00:15:18.359 --> 00:15:24.359
So here I've got two files, foo.r, I've just got this very silly and simple function, which

00:15:24.359 --> 00:15:30.559
has a mistake in it, which you can see, which we'll fix shortly, and then I've got a test.

00:15:30.559 --> 00:15:38.280
So I run foo, I expect it as a character vector, and then I'm going to use this new expectation,

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:43.559
expect snapshot output, and this doesn't have what the expected value is, because it's going

00:15:43.559 --> 00:15:46.200
to save it to test.

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:51.159
So the first time I run this, it's going to say, warning, create snapshot reference,

00:15:51.159 --> 00:16:01.479
and it creates a new file, and I forgot to put the correct directory in here, inside

00:16:01.479 --> 00:16:06.280
the test that directory, it's going to create a new directory called snaps, underscore snaps,

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.840
and inside that, it's going to have a file called foo.md, right?

00:16:10.919 --> 00:16:17.400
So our R file is called foo.r, our test file is called test-foo.r, and then our snapshot

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:21.799
for that, the snapshot file is going to be called foo.md.

00:16:21.799 --> 00:16:26.960
So all of these are just named, have a strong naming convention, so you can easily find

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:31.960
which snapshot corresponds to which test, which corresponds to which R file.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:33.239
So what does that snapshot contain?

00:16:33.239 --> 00:16:38.599
Well, it's a markdown file, I'll kind of explain the syntax shortly, but we use a heading to

00:16:38.679 --> 00:16:46.599
indicate that this is the test, and then it's going to put the output of that test directly

00:16:46.599 --> 00:16:48.919
in that file.

00:16:48.919 --> 00:16:53.799
So now if I run it again, if I run that test again, the test is going to work, because

00:16:53.799 --> 00:16:58.359
nothing's changed, and so the test will pass.

00:16:58.359 --> 00:17:05.520
If I change it to fix that typo, I run the test again, I'm getting an error, saying that

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:11.199
the previous value was something conflicted, and the new value is something complicated.

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:17.359
Now the downside of snapshot tests is that there's no way to know what is correct, so

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:20.520
you as a human now have to step in and intervene.

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:26.000
So if this is correct, if you really did mean to make this change, you can run snapshot

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.400
accept, and that will accept the change.

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:34.479
And the way that this works is that when you have this value, when something is changed,

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:39.520
there will be a new markdown file, which contains the new value.

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:43.199
If you accept it, then it will replace that with the old value.

00:17:44.319 --> 00:17:46.640
Okay, so that's kind of the big picture.

00:17:48.719 --> 00:17:54.160
So let's just dive into that for a slightly more realistic example.

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:55.359
Start with a simple one.

00:17:55.359 --> 00:18:01.040
So I have this package, I have the same test which I copied before, and I'm going to run

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:01.599
this test.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:08.079
And I'm going to run this test by pressing commands T, which is a shortcut for DevTools

00:18:09.359 --> 00:18:10.160
test file.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:16.479
So this keyboard shortcut takes advantage of that convention, that if you've got a file

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:20.239
called foo.r, the corresponding test will be test.foo.

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:30.239
And so this says I've added a new snapshot, this is the value of that snapshot, I can

00:18:30.239 --> 00:18:34.319
look at it, there's this markdown file again, which I'll explain shortly.

00:18:34.319 --> 00:18:41.359
And then if I run that test again, you'll see that all the tests have passed.

00:18:42.959 --> 00:18:46.560
The other thing, if you've used DevTools test file before, which I'll talk about briefly

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:51.599
later, is there's now a slightly different display, a slightly more compact display to

00:18:51.599 --> 00:18:56.160
hopefully make it easier to run tests for a single file interactively.

00:18:57.119 --> 00:19:03.199
So I'm going to change this, I'm going to correct that typo, I'm going to test again,

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:08.880
and now the test fails because the snapshot has changed.

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:13.359
So it shows you the current value, which is something complicated, and it shows you the

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:15.520
previous value, which is something complicated.

00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:21.680
Now, if this is a deliberate change, you can run snapshot accept.

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:27.920
If this wasn't a deliberate change, oh, that was just a typo, I can fix it and rerun and

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:29.199
all my tests pass again.

00:19:29.839 --> 00:19:33.760
So if you've ever used verify output, this is a little bit different because verify output

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:40.400
automatically updates the kind of true known value on disk, which forced you to use it

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:41.920
with GIT, basically.

00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:48.400
So I'm going to fix this, the test fails, you can see now in my snaps directory, I've

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:55.040
got foo, that's the foo.md, that's the previous value, and I've got foo.new.md, which is the

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:55.680
new value.

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:02.719
So I look at this, I decide that is actually correct, and then I can just copy and paste

00:20:02.719 --> 00:20:18.719
this, and now foo.md has the correct result, and I can test that again.

00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:26.719
Okay, so let's look at a slightly more complicated example.

00:20:26.719 --> 00:20:35.839
So this is a bullets function, and it's basically used to create HTML bullets.

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:44.000
So it looks like this.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:49.680
And this is like a little annoying to test, because if you're going to put this in a test,

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:54.719
you'd have to escape all of these new lines and kind of carefully manage all the white

00:20:54.719 --> 00:20:56.319
spaces, it's just a pain.

00:20:56.880 --> 00:21:00.640
To test this code, it's a little easier to use a snapshot test.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:12.959
So I can run this test, and now here is a test snapshot file with multiple expectations

00:21:12.959 --> 00:21:13.599
in it.

00:21:13.599 --> 00:21:20.719
The first one, I am just using a bullet with a single bullet, and the second also has a

00:21:20.719 --> 00:21:22.319
single bullet and also sets the ID.

00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:26.640
So if I later want to change this bullets function, maybe I've decided actually I don't

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:27.439
want this indent.

00:21:28.319 --> 00:21:29.119
Let's get rid of that.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:31.839
I rerun the test.

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:36.719
Again, the changes use Waldo to highlight what's changed.

00:21:36.719 --> 00:21:42.239
So it's a little bit hard to see this, but this is the thing that's the same.

00:21:42.239 --> 00:21:43.359
It's in gray.

00:21:43.359 --> 00:21:44.719
What's changed?

00:21:44.880 --> 00:21:53.520
We can see there is now no space where there was before.

00:21:56.239 --> 00:22:00.880
So I look at this, I decide, yep, that's a deliberate change, and then I run snapshot

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:05.599
except bullets to update that snapshot.

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:11.680
And that basically is snapshot testing.

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:16.640
Of course, there's more documentation, and I think it will take a little while to get

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:18.319
your head around it all.

00:22:18.319 --> 00:22:20.959
I've shown you expect snapshot output here.

00:22:20.959 --> 00:22:25.280
There's also expect snapshot, which, as well as printed output, also captures messages,

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:26.319
warnings, errors.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:32.640
There's also expect snapshot error if you want to capture specifically just error messages.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:36.400
And then we've got expect snapshot value, which captures return value.

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:38.400
So this is a little bit different.

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:44.000
This is if you, for example, wanted to test the output from a complicated function, you

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.400
just want to make sure it doesn't change without warning.

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:48.400
You can use expect snapshot value.

00:22:51.439 --> 00:22:54.800
And then again, of course, there's the vignette, which you can look at.

00:22:55.760 --> 00:23:00.079
Well, I guess I can't show it because I've installed the development version of the package

00:23:00.079 --> 00:23:01.119
which doesn't have the vignettes.

00:23:01.119 --> 00:23:02.959
But you can go to the website.

00:23:02.959 --> 00:23:04.959
Actually, let's just go to the website.

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:13.280
And then we can see all these vignettes.

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:14.959
Here's one on snapshot testing.

00:23:16.959 --> 00:23:18.959
And then we can see all these vignettes.

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:20.560
And then we can see all these vignettes.

00:23:20.560 --> 00:23:22.160
Here's one on snapshot testing.

00:23:24.719 --> 00:23:28.160
I'm just giving you a little bit more detail about what I just talked about.

00:23:32.479 --> 00:23:35.920
So the only other thing to mention is just what do these files look like?

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:37.680
Why are they markdown files?

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:42.239
Well, if you're writing this, this package is a collaborative project and you're using

00:23:42.239 --> 00:23:47.760
GitHub or some other tool where you do code review, it's really important to make sure

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:52.719
it's really important that these snapshots be human readable because when someone goes

00:23:52.719 --> 00:23:56.479
to review your code, they need to go look at the snapshot and say, is this a reasonable

00:23:56.479 --> 00:23:57.520
change or not?

00:23:57.520 --> 00:23:58.640
So they use markdown.

00:23:59.839 --> 00:24:05.359
Each file, again, is there's one snapshot file per test file, which normally corresponds

00:24:05.359 --> 00:24:07.760
to our file in the R directory.

00:24:08.560 --> 00:24:10.880
There's a heading for the test name.

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:15.359
And then if you have multiple snapshot expectations and a single test, they're separated by the

00:24:15.359 --> 00:24:17.040
horizontal row with three dashes.

00:24:18.239 --> 00:24:27.760
One thing that I'm working on at the moment and some help from Joshua Kunst is a Shiny

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:32.959
app that will help you review all of these differences and accept them or reject them

00:24:32.959 --> 00:24:36.079
with by clicking buttons rather than typing stuff at the console.

00:24:36.079 --> 00:24:41.119
And the other big part of that is providing tools for doing image snapshots as well.

00:24:41.119 --> 00:24:46.719
So this is something that we've implemented in two places and Shiny test, which is used

00:24:46.719 --> 00:24:50.880
for testing Shiny and VDiffer, which is used for testing ggpod2.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:55.680
The idea is they're going to pull out the common code, centralize and test that and

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.239
invest a bunch in this whole snapshotting idea.

00:24:58.239 --> 00:25:02.560
So you've got a really nice workflow if you do need to do image tests.

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:06.479
Image tests are complicated because they can change for all sorts of reasons unrelated

00:25:06.479 --> 00:25:07.119
to your code.

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:12.560
But sometimes they're all you have and they are a really important part of testing both

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:14.800
Shiny itself and ggpod2 itself.

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:18.479
Okay, so that's snapshot tests.

00:25:19.199 --> 00:25:24.319
Main idea of snapshot tests is that compared to regular unit tests, which have the expected

00:25:24.319 --> 00:25:31.119
results in the test file, snapshot tests store the expected results in another file, which

00:25:31.119 --> 00:25:38.000
makes them suitable for testing large output, output with quote marks and backslashes in

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.319
it and for testing things that you simply cannot describe with text like images.

00:25:42.719 --> 00:25:46.079
Next, I wanted to talk briefly about parallel tests.

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:50.160
This is still work in progress by Gabor Chadi.

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:55.040
And again, you're going to have to activate this specifically for your package again by

00:25:55.040 --> 00:25:59.680
putting another line in your description, config, test that parallel true.

00:26:00.239 --> 00:26:02.160
But the payoff for this is pretty big.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:06.239
It's going to run your tests on multiple processes.

00:26:06.239 --> 00:26:07.599
Multiple processes.

00:26:08.160 --> 00:26:14.640
So if you have long running tests, this is going to make a big improvement to the total

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:16.160
running time of your tests.

00:26:16.719 --> 00:26:20.719
Now, the downside is like there's a little bit of overhead associated with that starting

00:26:20.719 --> 00:26:26.959
out multiple R packages, multiple R processes, loading all the code in those.

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:28.880
So there's a little bit of overhead.

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:32.800
So if your tests are very fast, like if your tests all run in under a second, it's probably

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:35.040
not going to have a huge impact.

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:40.160
But if you've got tests that take five or ten seconds, the whole test suite takes minutes,

00:26:40.719 --> 00:26:44.479
then this should hopefully have a really big positive impact on your workflow.

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:47.119
There are some downsides.

00:26:49.199 --> 00:26:54.640
As well as this big upside of speed, tests will now kind of effectively run in stochastic

00:26:54.640 --> 00:27:01.359
order because you'll have like four processes and each process takes kind of the next test

00:27:01.359 --> 00:27:02.400
in the queue.

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:08.079
And so depending on exactly how long each test takes to run, the tests might get run

00:27:08.079 --> 00:27:10.000
in a different order.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:16.400
And this basically means if you have any dependency between your tests, which is relatively

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:19.280
easy to introduce because normally they will run in alphabetical order.

00:27:20.479 --> 00:27:24.959
If there is any dependency between your test files, you'll get like random test failures

00:27:24.959 --> 00:27:30.319
that occur sometimes but don't occur other times depending on exactly which order the

00:27:30.319 --> 00:27:31.439
tests are run in.

00:27:31.439 --> 00:27:35.199
In other words, this is like a dependency debugging nightmare.

00:27:35.839 --> 00:27:39.920
So we're still thinking about tools to kind of ensure that if that happens to you, we've

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:44.160
got some mode debugging mode you can switch on to get more insight.

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:48.560
And then also, if you have used like global setup or teardown, for example, like you set

00:27:48.560 --> 00:27:55.040
up a database or some CSV file for all of your tests, you're going to need to think

00:27:55.040 --> 00:28:00.959
that through in a little bit more detail because those setup and teardown files are

00:28:00.959 --> 00:28:03.119
now run by multiple processes.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:08.000
So there's going to be a little bit of work to convert your tests to use Parallel.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:09.839
We're still working on this.

00:28:09.839 --> 00:28:12.319
You know, there's a vignette if you want to learn more and want to try it out.

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:16.319
But we're hopeful that this will make a big impact if you've got long running tests.

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:22.640
So I've talked about this idea of the third edition.

00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:24.160
This is a special mode.

00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:27.839
You'll have to switch on if you want to use all the latest and greatest test that features.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:36.719
We've talked about Waldo, which makes comparisons or test makes test failures from expect equal

00:28:36.719 --> 00:28:38.560
and friends much, much easier.

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:40.479
We talked about snapshotting tests.

00:28:40.479 --> 00:28:42.880
We talked about running tests in Parallel.

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:46.640
Now I just want to show you kind of a bunch of little features that I think are kind of

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:46.880
cool.

00:28:48.719 --> 00:28:53.599
So in the course of working on test that for this release made a bunch of improvements

00:28:53.599 --> 00:28:54.880
to the reporters.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:29:00.959
The reporters are the things that actually go and generate the results.

00:29:00.959 --> 00:29:05.040
So when I press test, this is done by a reporter.

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:08.880
If I press command shift T to run all of the tests, these are different reporters.

00:29:09.680 --> 00:29:13.920
One reporter that you never normally use is called stop.

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:17.439
You don't normally call it explicitly, but it's called stop reporter.

00:29:17.439 --> 00:29:18.959
That's what happens.

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:24.160
And that's the test that's run.

00:29:25.119 --> 00:29:28.400
So that's the reporter that's run when you run a test interactively.

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:34.640
So here I'm just running a test, which is not working for probably reasons that I need

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:35.839
to look into.

00:29:35.839 --> 00:29:43.439
But if I create a share of another example over here, if I run this test, this is the

00:29:43.439 --> 00:29:44.239
stop reporter.

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:47.599
Now it clearly tells you that your test passed.

00:29:50.239 --> 00:29:51.520
And it gives you some emoji.

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:58.319
If your test does not pass, it nicely displays the failures.

00:29:59.839 --> 00:30:01.760
And it also displays any warnings.

00:30:02.319 --> 00:30:06.719
And really conveniently, it also displays the backtrace for the warning.

00:30:06.719 --> 00:30:10.640
So if you've got warnings in any of your tests now, they get a full backtrace.

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:13.280
You can figure out exactly where that warning came from.

00:30:14.319 --> 00:30:22.000
One of my kind of pet peeves is, let me do this, is this.

00:30:27.520 --> 00:30:30.479
I have partial matching warnings turned on.

00:30:30.479 --> 00:30:34.479
And if this occurs somewhere deep inside a function, inside a function, inside another

00:30:34.479 --> 00:30:37.040
function, it's really hard to track down.

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:42.319
Now in your test, you get this nice backtrace so you can figure out exactly what sequence

00:30:42.319 --> 00:30:44.719
of functions leads to that problem.

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:47.439
OK.

00:30:47.439 --> 00:30:51.520
So that's the stop reporter, which is used in debugging.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:57.040
So now uses color, uses emoji, and generally gives you more information about problems

00:30:57.040 --> 00:30:58.880
when you're interactively running tests.

00:30:59.439 --> 00:31:02.640
I showed you earlier that compact progress reporter.

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:09.439
That is the single line here, which gives you kind of running.

00:31:09.439 --> 00:31:11.839
This is a little bit lower, a little bit fast.

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:19.199
We could do slow test to expect true system.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:30.079
So just doing a little loop here, which is going to do an expectation,

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:32.880
and then sleep for a little bit.

00:31:34.079 --> 00:31:36.880
So you can see it counts up a little slower.

00:31:36.880 --> 00:31:48.800
So you get like a running progress bar in some sense of all the tests that are running

00:31:48.800 --> 00:31:50.400
so you know exactly what's going on.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:01.839
I've made the regular reporter, which you see most often when you're running all the

00:32:01.839 --> 00:32:03.280
tests in your package.

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:12.160
The biggest thing is I have added a bunch of new praise that uses more emoji,

00:32:12.719 --> 00:32:14.079
because I think emoji are fun.

00:32:15.839 --> 00:32:23.119
These random praise kind of veer into a little bit into dad joke territory.

00:32:23.119 --> 00:32:28.239
But hopefully that's just something, a fun little feature of TestPad that keeps you motivated

00:32:28.239 --> 00:32:30.640
and keeps you going when your tests aren't working well.

00:32:31.199 --> 00:32:36.479
And finally, the last reporter is the check reporter that's run inside of our command

00:32:36.479 --> 00:32:37.119
check.

00:32:37.119 --> 00:32:39.359
Now it reports all of the problems.

00:32:39.359 --> 00:32:42.319
So it also reports warnings and skips tests.

00:32:42.319 --> 00:32:46.800
It tells you all of your skips tests by type, which is really useful for checking that you

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:49.839
haven't accidentally skipped tests that you meant to run.

00:32:49.839 --> 00:32:57.280
And it also creates an RDS file with a machine readable list of all of the tests.

00:32:57.280 --> 00:33:00.800
That's probably not something you're going to use directly, but it is something that

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:06.160
we will start to build into our tooling so that things like GitHub actions can give you

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:09.199
nicer displays of your tests and so on.

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:19.280
We've also made a few changes to the way that the condition functions work.

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:23.599
So here I have a function that calls warn and message.

00:33:24.479 --> 00:33:32.079
And now if a condition like a message, a warning, or an error is not explicitly caught by your

00:33:32.079 --> 00:33:34.160
expectation, it will continue to bubble up.

00:33:34.959 --> 00:33:46.079
So if I run this line, if I run this line, this expectation passes.

00:33:46.079 --> 00:33:50.959
It does find a warning called hi, but the message called bye still bubbles up.

00:33:51.839 --> 00:33:57.199
Or if I say I expect a message called bye, I'll see a warning called hi.

00:33:57.199 --> 00:34:03.439
So if I want to capture both of them, I need to use expect message and expect warning together.

00:34:03.439 --> 00:34:07.599
This hopefully will give you better control over exactly what's going on.

00:34:07.599 --> 00:34:10.719
It's going to cause a few more warnings in your tests.

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:17.120
These won't cause your package to fail our commands check, but they will require a little

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:21.840
bit of work to make sure that those tests are as you expect.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:27.760
If you want to just ignore them, you can still, rather than using expectations,

00:34:27.760 --> 00:34:36.879
you can just switch to the base functions, suppress messages and suppress warnings,

00:34:36.879 --> 00:34:38.159
if you don't care about them.

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:45.760
Now, you might notice here that we've got expectations nested inside of expectations,

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.199
and you might kind of naturally think, well, why can't I use the pipe for that?

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:55.679
Unfortunately, you cannot currently do that because the pipe eagerly evaluates everything.

00:34:56.479 --> 00:35:06.000
So if I do this, you get a bye and a hi, and then this fails because this is called before

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:06.879
this is called.

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:12.800
We will start to announce a new work in Magruder that will make this work

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:18.320
and hopefully make Magruder a little more compatible with the

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:24.719
native pipe that is unlikely to appear in the next version of R as well.

00:35:26.879 --> 00:35:33.439
Okay, so that also means if you're one of the, I don't know, 10 people in the world who use the

00:35:33.439 --> 00:35:37.280
all arguments, so expect warning, expect message, that's now deprecated.

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:41.679
You have to take a slightly different approach, but I'm pretty confident that's going to be a

00:35:41.679 --> 00:35:50.159
much nicer API overall and shouldn't change existing behavior too much.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:58.560
And the last thing is if you've ever used expect error and it gives you this message to set the

00:35:58.560 --> 00:36:01.840
class, we no longer encourage you to do that.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:06.879
It kind of fixed one type of test fragility, basically the cost of just introducing a

00:36:06.879 --> 00:36:12.239
different type of fragility, and so now you're better off just using expect snapshot error if

00:36:12.239 --> 00:36:18.080
you want to check that a specific error occurs because that just gives you a bunch of nice

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:20.639
features for managing the change over time.

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:26.399
Okay, so I'm just about to wrap up, which is great.

00:36:26.399 --> 00:36:27.919
So there's plenty of time for questions.

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.320
So what have I talked about today?

00:36:30.320 --> 00:36:34.239
First, test that 3.0 is coming out soon.

00:36:34.239 --> 00:36:39.199
I should say we'll probably start the release process in about a month, which means it's at

00:36:39.199 --> 00:36:41.120
least two months before it's on CRAN.

