00:36:54.560 --> 00:37:00.879
So the third edition is going to be part of test that 3.0, which will be on CRAN and at least,

00:37:01.520 --> 00:37:04.560
well, the soonest possible is probably two months.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:06.560
It's likely to be a little longer than that.

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:10.000
The third edition you will have to deliberately opt into.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:15.360
That gives you a bunch of new features at the cost of doing a little bit of work to clean up

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:16.399
old APIs.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:23.120
The new edition uses Waldo to make comparisons, which will hopefully make your test failures

00:37:23.120 --> 00:37:24.479
much easier to debug.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:30.239
It provides snapshot tests, which are an alternative form of testing where the expected

00:37:30.239 --> 00:37:37.199
results are stored on separate files rather than inline and code, and then the test that

00:37:37.199 --> 00:37:43.360
provides some functions to help manage those files so that you can accept changes when you

00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:47.280
have made them deliberately or revert changes when you've made them accidentally.

00:37:48.479 --> 00:37:54.639
Test that 3.0 will also introduce parallel testing, which, again, will be a little bit of

00:37:55.120 --> 00:38:00.800
setup work just to make sure your global setup and teardown works appropriately and you don't

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:04.719
accidentally have any dependencies between your tests.

00:38:06.080 --> 00:38:10.639
But the payoff will be if you have slow tests, they should run much, much faster because they'll

00:38:10.639 --> 00:38:11.760
run in parallel.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:16.959
And then, finally, I showed you a bunch of goodies, many of them featuring an emoji that

00:38:16.959 --> 00:38:20.719
will hopefully make your day-to-day life using test that a little bit more fun, a little bit

00:38:20.719 --> 00:38:21.280
more pleasant.

